{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_cartier_ver01/data/sn94060041/00542866779/1930083001/0577.xml":{"full_text":"VIRGINIA G. 0. P.\nCOLD TO BYARS\u2019\nSENATE HOPES\nLeaders Loath To Incur Repe\ntition Of Brown Coalition\nFiasco\nRichmond, Va., Aug. 24\u2014As the\nRepublican State Convention at Roa\nnoke next Saturday approaches oppo\nsition is developing to the proposal\nto indorse or to nominate as the\nG. O. P. candidate for the United\n.States Senate J. Cloyd Byars, anti\nGlass and 1928 anti-Smith Democrat,\nwho has announced himself as an in\ndependent aspirant for the seat in\nWashington now held by the Lynch\n\"burg publisher.\nThe fiasco that marked the out\ncome last year of the coalition Gub\nernatorial candidacy of Dr. William\n.Moseley Brown is still fresh in the\n\u2022minds of many Republican leaders.\nThey are not anxious for another\ndose of coalition politics with the\nanti-Smith element of the opposition\nparty,, formally or otherwise.\nThe anti-Byars, Republican point\n'out that the G. 0. P. vote in Vir\nginia, with Brown as a coalition can\ndidate, dropped 64,000 votes, while\nthe Democrats gained 30,000 com\npared with the Hoover-Smith ballot\ning in 1928, and the nomination of\nByars this year would mean simply\nanother confession that the Republi\ncan party has no timber within its\nown ranks for a State-wide office\nand the Brown fiasco would be re\npeated.\nWith the convention only a week\n\u00aboff there is a total lack of senti\nment in favor of any one candidate\nfor the Senatorial nomination. The\nrank and file say the leaders have a\nstrong candidate in mind, and the\nleaders say there has been no crys\ntalization for anyone, and that the\nmatter will be threshed out when\nthe leaders and delegates gather at\nRoanoke from all parts of the State.\nH. B. McConnac, Winchester wool\nen manufacturer and business man,\nfor whom a strong sentiment pre\nvailed, has told his friends that he\ncould not take the nomination under\nany circumstances. If he had given\nhis consent he undoubtedly would be\nmamed.\nC. Bascom Slemp has put thumbs\n-down on suggestion of his nomina\n'tion, and Henry W. Anderson and\nRobert H. Angell, the latter State\nRepublican chairman, likewise say\ntheir private interests prevent them\n'taking up the fight.\nThere is some sentiment for select\ning the candidate from one of the\ntthree Congressional districts which\nwere carried by the Republicans in\n1928 for Congress. This sentiment\nis based upon the theory that candi\ndates from the Second, Seventh or\nNinth would help the fights of Men\nalcus Lankford, J. A. Garber or\nJoseph C. Shaffer for re-election to\nthe House.\nJ. W. Rivercomb, Clifton Forge\nlawyer, has been spoken of for the\nnomination, and if he is named he\nprobably will accept. Mr. Rivercomb,\nhowever, hails from the Tenth dis\ntrict, now represented in Congress\nby Harry St. George Tucker, of Lex\nington.\nUncertainty prevails as to wnai\nthe Republican leaders will advise\nthe convention to do. Whatever\nthese leaders advise will be done, it\nis generally conceded, even if their\nrecommendation means the indorse\nment of Byars, notwithstanding the\nopposition to him in many sections.\nThis feeling of uncertainty is cre\nated largely on the conviction that\nthere is no chance of defeating\nGlass. Leaders of both -parties feel\n\u2022that this is a Democratic year in\nVirginia, and the nomination of a\ncandidate to oppose the Lynchburg\nman will be simply a matter of\nform. There is a sentiment, how\n\u25a0ever, among the leaders, unwilling as\nmany of them are to take the\nnomination, that some one must be\nnamed in order to save the State\nparty\u2019s forces with the Administra\ntion and national leaders in Wash\nington, although they know the fight\nis a hopeless one.\nIf a Republican is named and By\nars continues his independent can\ndidacy, the opposition forces to\nGlass will be split, thus further en\nhancing the chances of his election.\nWith the decline of Bishop Can\nnon\u2019s political power in Virginia and\nthe absence of prohibition and re\nligion as -vote-swaying factors, the\nByars candidacy is not held formid\nable by political leaders .of either\nparty. In fact, the only issue the\nanti-Glass forces have is that the\nLynchburg candidate attacked Bishop\nCannon and the preachers in 1928\nand this talk is not starting any\nred fires, as it did two years ago.\nGlass cannot be attacked on .his pro\nhibition record, as he is and has been\nthe most consistent prohibitionist,\npersonally and politically, in public\noffice in the State, except on the\n.-grounds of his support of Smith, and\nFive-Figure\nBusiness In\nVillage Of 150\nRead How The Bloxoms Have\nDone This And Are\nStill Growing\ncarload\nTIRES\u2019\nAuro supply\nStory of Bloxom Auto Supply, in\nthe tire business in Mappsville, Vir\nginia, is one worth repeating. From\nsales of $150 in 1922, their business\nhas grown by leaps and bounds,\nuntil they hit a generous five-figure\nbusiness in 1929< and look forward\nto nearly doubling that in 1930.\nThe story is more interesting when\nit is known that Mappsville is a vil\nlage of 150 people, containing just\n79 motor vehicles. The village is\nthree miles from the nearest rail\nroad station, but is on the main road\nfrom Philadelphia to Cape Charles.\nWith such a location, one wonders,\nof course, how such a volume was\ndeveloped.\nThe business was originally Blox\nom Brothers, dealers in Willys\nKnight and Overland automobiles. In\n1925, B. S. Bloxom and son, A. B.\nBloxom, decided to go into tires on\na large scale along with enlarging j\n\ntheir new car accommodations. They\nbuilt a one-story concrete showroom\nand service station, 64x96, with all\nmodern equipment. This showroom\nand service station has the most up\nto-date service facilities available on\nthe Eastern Shore of Virginia.\nTheir rapid increase in tire sales\nis attributed to county newspaper\nadvertising, direct mail and outside\nsolicitation. All the territory around\nMappsville is combed thoroughly for\nbusiness, A. B. Bloxom making a\ntwo-day road trip every week.\nAlthough this Goodyear dealer\nsells a car that comes equipped With\na tire other than Goodyear, a good\nshare of his business comes from\nchanging over original equipment to\nGoodyear and using the original\nequipment for spares.\nAt Spring Dating time, the Blox\noms ordered the first carload of\nGoodyear tires that was ever ship\nped on the Eastern Shore.\nThe Bloxoms capitalized on it by\ntaking a picture of the car, with a\nlarge banner on it, and running a\ni full-page ad, including t^jjs picture,\nin all the county newspapers. The\nj result in new business was surpris\ning, according to Bloxom.\nj The Bloxoms attribute their suc\ncess in the tire business to outside\nj solicitation, consistent use of news\npapers and the aggressive pushing of\nPathfinder tires at mail order prices.\nI Last year, their sales were over 60\nper cent Pathfinders and so far this\nyear, the sales remain about the\nsame.\nThe accompanying two pictures\ngive an idea as to the layout of their\nplace of business. Mr. Bloxom is\non the left of the picture and his\ni son on the right. Service equipment\nincludes air-compressor, tire chang\ners, battery equipment and the like,\nj \u2014The Goodyear News.\nthen he, like many Prohibition-Demo\ncrats, voted for Smith primarily to\nkeep intact their party organization\nin the State.\nByars\u2019 candiaacy, like that of Dr.\nBrown\u2019s last year, .rill lack the able\ngeneralship which Hoover\u2019s had in\n1928 from the anti-Smith forces.\nBishop Cannon two years ago was\nstill a powerful factor in Virginia\npolitics, although his power as one\nof the dominant leaders in Demo\ncratic ranks had been broken when\nHarry Flood Byrd won the Guber\nnatorial nomination in the face of\nCannon\u2019s and the Anti-Saloon Lea\ngue\u2019s veiled opposition.\nWhen Byrd became Governor, Can\nnon lost his grip upon the Virginia\nGeneral Assembly. There are many\npolitical observers in Virginia today\nwho believe that Hoover\u2019s victory in\n1928 in the State was far more\nlargely due to the leadership of Can\nnon, former State Senator George N.\nConard, former Senator W. L. An\ndrews and other men of that type\nto the Republican leadership of\nSlemp and others.\nIf Bishop Cannon should come back\nfrom Brazil and plunge into the\nVirginia fight against Glass, he\nwould find the wind blowing against\nhim instead of with him. Glass like\nCannon is a Methodist, and like him\na prohibitionist. The only thing the\nbishop could say against him Would\nbe that he voted for and supported\nA1 Smith in 1928.\nWith the collapse of the Hoover\nprosperity, with business at its low\nest ebb in nearly a score of years,\nwith the failure 'of the Administra\ntion to maintain the \u201cgood times\u201d\nas promised in 1928, and with\nthousands of people out of work,\nthe A1 Smith bugaboo is not going\nto throw the Virginia people into\nconvulsions this year as it did in\n1928. In fact, there are many peo\nple now saying that if A1 Smith\nhad been elected the country would\nnot have had that Hoover-inflated\nstock market, which later collapsed\nand drained out of the State to New\nYork losses exceeding the estimated\n$100,000,000 loss inflicted upon the\nVirginia farmers by Hie drought. It\nis said that the stock market col\nlapse drained out of Lynchburg,\nSenators Glass\u2019 home city, approxi\nmately $19,000,000.\nSome of the Republican leaders, it\nis declared, will attempt to minimize\nthe business depression by blaming\nthe drought, but the Democrats are\nplanning to come back and reply by\nsaying the Hoover stock market col\nlapse cost the Virginia people far\nmore than the drought and- the Ad\nministration should have had busi\nness foresight enough to anticipate\nthe business depression and the stock\nmarket collapse if it could not have\nprevented the drought.\nHODGES IS NAMED\nTO PRISON BOARD;\nSucceeds BuIIington, President\nOf Richmond City\u2019s Cham\nber Of Commerce\n\nRichmond, Va.t Aug. 26 Major j\nLeRoy Hodges, managing director of\nthe Virginia State Chamber of Com\nmerce, has been appointed by Gover\nnor Pollard to membership on the\nState Prison Board to fill a vacancy\ncaused iby the resignation of R. McC.\nBuIIington, president of the Rich\nmond Chamber of Commerce.\nThe appointment is for the remain\nder of the term of Mr. BuIIington,\nexpiring March 1, 1934.\nMajor Hodges served as president\nof the State Prison Board from\nApril, 1920, until his resignation\nfrom the board early in 1926. Dur\ning his administration as head of the\nprison system of the State, Major\nHodges instituted measures which\nwon him national reputation.\nPersonal aide and secretary to\nGovernor Westmoreland Davis during\nlatter\u2019s\nthe latter\u2019s administration, Major\nHodges also was State Budget Direc\ntor during the administrations of\nGovernors Davis and Trinkle. He\nwas secretary of the Virginia Com\nmission of Economy and Efficiency,\n1916-17, and special field representa\ntive of the United States Food Ad\nministration during 1917.\nOther members of the State Prison\nBoard are Walker C. Cottrell, Rich\nmond, chairman; Clyde W. Saunders,\nJudge T. Gray Haddon, Richmond,\nand James Brockwell, Petersburg.\nBREAKING THE BARRIER\nFive years ago off-campus classes\nwere conducted in only five Virginia\ncities for the benefit of 186 men\nand women doing the work of the\nworld and at the same time continu\ning their education. Last year ten\ntimes as many students entered even\ning classes in 33 cities, towns and\nvillages, from Alexandria to Clarks\nville, from Norfolk to Coeburn,\ncovering an area of 30,000 miles.\nFifteen institutions of higher edu\ncation in Virginia have banded to\ngether in a cooperative program to\nfurnish competent instruction in any\nsubject selected by a group of fifteen\nstudents. They offer their services\nto the people everywhere who feel\nthe desire to \u201cbe something more than\nthey are now and to do their work\nbetter than they now do it.\u201d Their\njoint announcement lists for organi\nzation in October 153 courses offered\nby 91 specialists in 18 fields of\nknowledge.\nLet us submit you samples of\nengraved or printed wedding an\nnouncements or invitations. First\n'lass work only and prompt delivery\nPRESBYTERIAN SYNOD\nMEETS IN RICHMOND\nTUESDAY, SEPTEMBER 9\nInterests Of Educational Insti\ntutions One Of Most Important\nMatters To Be Considered\nRichmond, Va., Aug. 27\u2014The Pres\nbyterian Synod of Virginia will hold\nits 143rd annual session at Union\nTheological Seminary here, begin\nning on September 9th at 11 a. m.,\nand continuing in session for three\ndays.\nThe opening sermon will be\npreached by Rev. Dr. Thornton S.\nWilson, of Halifax County. This will\nbe followed by the Communion Ser\nvice, conducted by Rev. Dr. J. A.\nMacLean, pastor of the Ginter Park\nChurch, of Richmond, and Rev. F.\nM. Allen, pastor of the church at\nClarksville. After this a new mod\nerator will be elected.\nOne of the most important matters\nof business to occupy the attention\nof the Synod will be the interests of\nits educational institutions. They are\nUnion Theological Seminary, Hamp\nden-Sydney College, Mary Baldwin\nCollege, Danville Military Academy.\nOther institutions which will call\nfor the attention of the body were\nthe Massanetta Bible Conference, the\nSynod\u2019s Orphan\u2019s Home at Lynch\nburg, and the Sunnyside Home for\nLadies at Danville.\nOne of the matters which will be\nof special interest will be the report\nof a committee appointed last year\nto suggest plans for the reorganiza\ntion of the work of the Synod. This\nwill deal especially with the work of\nHome Missions in the Synod.\nAnother matter of interest will be\nthe report of another committee to\nwhich was referred last year a com\nmunication from two members of the\nBaltimore Conference of the Metho\ndist Episcopal Church, South, asking\nthat the Methodists be permitted to\njoin in the ownership and manage\nment of the Summer Bible Confer\nence Encampment at Massanetta\nSprings, near Harrisonburg, and in a\nschool, which it is proposed to es\ntablish there. Rev. D. T. S. Wilson\nis chairman of this committee.\nMemorials of the following six\ndeceased will be presented by com\nmittees appointed to prepare them:\nRev. A. C. Bridgman, D. D.; Rev.\nG. D. Moses, Rev. J, G. Reveley,\nRev. Frank Hoffman, Rev. Lapsley,\nRev. .William Chinn, D. D.\nThe territory of the Synod includes\nall of Virginia, except a part of the\nsouthwest section, and it takes in a\npart of northern West Virginia, the\nDistrict of Columbia and the South\nern part of Maryland.\nThe Synod has on its rolls 431\nchurches and 343 ministers. The\nmembership of the church is 63,606.\nSTATE ACQUIRES\nRARE VOLUMES FROM\nVA. PRINTING PRESSES\nPurchased At Sale Of Famous\nSaratoga Library Near Dill\nwyn Last Week\nRichmond, Va., Aug. 25\u2014Several\nold and rare volumes from Virginia\u2019s\nfirst printing presses have been ac\nquired by the State and William and\nMary College librarians, following an\nauction of the famous Saratoga\nlibrary at the old Hubbard home\nnear Dillwyn, between, Buckingham\nCourthouse and Farmville, last Mon\nday.\nj One of the three copies in exist\nence of the \u201cAets of the General\n\nj\nAssembly of 1777,\u201d printed in Wil\nliamsburg in that year, has been pur\nchased for William and Mary College\nby Dr. Earl <-G. Swem, college li\nbrarian and former assistant State\nlibrarian. Another volume purchased\nfor the Williamsburg school is a\ncopy of \u201cThe Complete Mariner,\u201d\na treatise on navigation carrying\ndemonstrations of logarithims done\nin hand by the author, E. L. James\nHubard, in Williamsburg in 1731.\nA history of Virginia, issued in\nj 1640, is numbered among those\nbooks destined for the shelves of\ni the State library, along with a sim\nilar history printed 103 years later,\nin 1743.\nj \u201cA view on the Conduct of the\nExecutive of Foreign Affairs of the\nUnited States,\u201d by James Monroe,\npublished by Benjamin F. Bache in\nPhiladelphia in 1797; \u201cCommittee Re\nports of the First Session of the\nSeventh Congress, Volume 1, 1798,*\nand copies of the Senate journals\nfor the 1816 and 1821, and other\nvolumes acquired for the State li\nbrary.\nOther old and rare volumes, which\nwere found in the library, left by E.\nW. Hubard upon his death several\nyears ago, are as follows:\n\u201cLes Comedies de Terrence,\u201d by\nMadame Davier, printed in 1700;\n\u201cP. Terrentie Carthagimensis Afii\nComediae Sex,\u201d first edition publish\ned in London in 1687, and \u201cQuinte\nCurce of Alexander the Great,\u201d pub\nlished in 1657.\nRailroads\nAtch., Top. Sante Fe\nRailway Company\nCanadian Pac. Ry. Co.\nIllinois Cent. R. R. Co.\nLouis. Nash. IL R. Co.\nN. Y. Central R. R Co.\nv Pennsylvania R. R. Co.\nSouthern Pacific Co.\nUnion Pacific R. R. Co.\nOils\nRoyal Dutch Company\n(New York Shares)\nStandard Oil Company\nof California\nStandard Oil Company\n(New Jersey)\nStandard Oil Company\nof New York\nTexas Corporation\nIndustrials\nAmerican Radiator A\nStandard Sanitary Corp.\nAmerican Tobacco Co.\n(Class B)\ndu Pont (E. I.) de Nemours\nCompany\nEastman Kodak Company\nof New Jersey\nGeneral Electric Co.\nIngersoll-Rand Company\nNational Biscuit Co.\nOtis Elevator Company\nUnited Fruit Company\nU. S. Steel Corporation\nWestinahouse Elec. A\nMfff. Company\nWoolworth (K W.) Co.\nUtilities\nAmerican Tel. A Tel. Co.\nCom. Gu Co. of N. Y.\nWestern Union Tel. Co.\nEarning Power\nNo Investment Is Stronger Than The\nEarning Power Underlying It\nThe demonstrated earning power of\nthis group of outstanding companies\nthrough good years and bad furnishes\nthe great bulwark of stability under\nlying North American .Trust Shares\nthe largest fixed trust.\nDeposited with the Guaranty Trust\nCompany of New York, Trustee,\nagainst the issuance of each 2,000\nNorth American Trush Shares, are\nfour shares each of these twenty\neight outstanding common stocks listed\non the New York Stock Exchange,\ntogether with $1200 cash reserve fund.\nThis security combines the investment\nfundamentals of safety, marketability\nand yield together with prospective\nenhancement of principal.\nFurther details on request.\nDAVIS WEST\nInvestment Securities\n100 Royster Building Phone 24090 NORFOLK, VIRGINIA\nUSE PERFECTION PACK\nSolid Bottom Tub Bushels\nFor White Potatoes and Sweet Potatoes\nYou will make money putting\npotatoes in these Baskets\nSpecify Perfection Pack and\nGive it a Trial\nPRICES ARE RIGHT\nHouston White Co.\nMILLSBORO, DELAWARE\nPhone 32","height":"26656","width":"19612"}}
